{"/service/ndnp/nbu/batch_nbu_fourtusker_ver01/data/sn93062828/00332899491/1945090101/0268.xml":{"full_text":"I\n/JUSTICE/EQUALITY\nEQUAL OPPORTUNITY _ PHONE HA.0800\n2420 GRANT ST\n\"Largest Accredited Negro Newspaper West of Chicago and North of KC\u2022\n1 a -s.'.i'si-.r: r ==^=^s= -.u-. t-\u2014 l1 1 1 \u2014^===^=g\nEntered as 2nd class matter at Post-oftice, Omaha, Nebr., Under Act of 0 1AXC\nMarch 8, 1874. Publishing Offices at 2420 Grant Street, Omaha. Nebr ScJ/turdSy, SGpt. I, 1945 w IOC Gr Copy OllP I8th Y63,r\u2014No. 30\nBK .ABOR DAY CELEBRATION PLANNED A T RIVERVIEW\nI EDITION\naLocal Nat,l\nI NEWS\nOrganized\nLabor Knows\nthe Score...\nBY WILLIAM nliEEY\nPresident. American Federation of\nof\nTHE VERY LIFE OF ORGAN\nIZED LABOR DEPENDS very\nlargely upon the establishment and\nesistence of democracy. For that\nreason, those who believe in organ\nized labor have worked too hard\nand sacrificed too much to feel\nkindly toward anything that threat\nens it.\nPrejudice and intolerance are\ncrimes agaiinst democracy. Tliere\nfon^ whenever someone asks you\nhow organized labor feel about rac-i\nial and religious intolerance. in\nquire of him as to how he feels a\nbout crime. To anyone who under\nstands the broader issues, the ans\nwer is as simple as that. Freedom\nis essential to the preservation of\ndemocracy. If and when we begin\nto limit it by insisting that it be de\nmcu buiiic auu ap|inru iu uiueis uc\u2014\ncause of racial or religious differ\nences. the list of exceptions grows\nand materializes until finally free\ndom for all is ended. For instance\nthe rights' of the worker, his free\ndom to organize into a union of his\nown choosing and to bargain col\nlectively for wages and decent con\nditions of living, are the first to be\ndestroyed if we seek to establish\nlimited freedom.\nAmerican workers are men and\nwomen of understanding. They\nfully appreciate and clearly under\nstand that a union which functions\ndemocratically and follows a policy\nfree from racial or religious dis\ncrimination rests upon a sound and\nenduring basis. They also know\nanrf. fully comprehend that an or\nganization whose members are mov\ned by feelings of prejudice and\nwhich limits its membership to cer\ntain racial or religious groups is\nstriking at its very vital essential\u2014\nthe establishment of unity and\nsolidarity. When and if organized\nlabor predicates membership in\nany union upon raca. Petition o\u00bbj\nancestry, it is helping to create a|\npotential anti-labor army that can\nbe used by labor-baiters to fight\nlabor unions, weaken its bargaining\npower and destroy its effective\nness.\nBecause organized labor is con\nscious of this fact, it is fully deter\nmined that the enemies of labor\nshall have no weapon to use or no\nsuch power to exercise. Working\nmen and women will maintain the\ntraditional position they have al\nways followed, to fight in the fore\nfront of the battle which has ad\nways been and always will be car\nried on against bigotry. Workers\nhave always supported and will\ncontinue to support the guarantees\nof the Constitution to all classes of\npeople.\nWe know' that difficulties are\nencountered in carrying out this\nprogram. There are those who\nhope to magnify prejudices and\nplay upon them and take advan\ntage of all human weaknesses, but\nthe membership of organized labor\nis didicated to the tasK or not only\nestablishing, but preserving trade\nunions as a democratic force. I\nknow that organized labor will\nContinue to maintain and practice\nequality of opportunity which is a\nbasic union principle, as well as a\nbasic principle of American life.\nAt our organization's annual Con\nvention which was held some\nmonths ago racial and religious bi\ngotry and discrimination were con\ndemned by a unanimous vote. The\nConvention reaffirmed a declaration\nwhich had been made at previous\nConventions calling upon the Amer\nican Federation of I-abor to \u201ccarry\non and expand the good work it has\nalready done so that the principle\nof industrial equality of all men\nwill be established beyond question\nin every section of the country.\nThe task of carrying out that man\ndate now rests with every union\nand with each and every worker\nwho is a member of said union. We\nmust not falter or fail. We must\nfight to maintain and preserve A\nmerican principles and the Ameri\ncan way of life. The faces of all\nworking men and women must be\nturned everlastingly against racial\nand religious discrimination and in\nfavor of freedom, liberty, equality,\nand democracy.\nCOMMISSION AGAINST\nDISCRIMINATION PROBES\nnegro ball clubs\nNew York\u2014(Calvin\u2019s News Service)\n\u2014New York State's Commission\nAgainst Discrimination has started\nprobing charges of discrimination\nagainst the race by local big league\nbaseball games.\nIn answer to a letter from City\nCouncilman Ben J. Davis who pointed\nout that the Council had passed reso\nlutions against discrimination by\nleague games, Henry C. Turner, presi\ndent of the Commission disclosed that\nthe Commission had begun work on\nthe affair. Too, Turner disclosed that\nhe had named two Commissioners,\nElmer A. Carter and Julian J. Reiss\nto study the situation and make rec\nommendations.\nPreliminary Survey\nShows Jobs Spotty\nIS THIS WHAT HE FOUGHT FOR?\nVMHfcT\nNA^ON^UnV\nyou?\nCourtesy Appreciate America, Inc,\nJob Tensions Are\nRising, Truman Told\nIn Plea For F. E. P. C.\nNew York-\u2014Mounting racial ten\nsion in 16 key states due to \u201cuncer\ntainty as to a fair chance for em\nployment in the postwar period\"\nwas reported to President Truman\nlast week bv the NAACP in a tele\ngraphic request for continuance of\nthe FEPC.\nThe NAACP telegram, signed by\nRoy Wilkins, assistant secretary,\ndeclared; \u201cFeeling is general that\nindifference and hostility to Fair\nEmployment Practice Committee\nmeans that government has aband\noned Negro Americans and they will\nhave to shift for themselves, bat\ntling disheartening old attitudes of\nprejudice.\u201d The complete telegram\nfollows:\n\u201cSince V-J Day the National As\nsociation for the Advancement of\nColored People has had a disturbing\nnumber of reports from our chap\nters in 16 key states indicating\nmounting tension springing from\nuncertainty as to fair chance for\nemployment in postwar period.\nFeeling is general that indifference\nand hostility to Fair Employment\nPractice Committee means that\ngovernment has abandoned Negro\nAmericans and they will have to\nshift for themselves battling dis\nheartening old attitudes of preju\ndice. Added to this is feeling of\nreturning Negro veterans that\ncountry is indifferent despite their\nsacrifices in war for democracy a\nbroad. In whatever conferences\nare held on fate of present FEPC.\nwe trust that your wise and sym\npathetic view as to its value in\nthis critical period will prevail. We\nmost earnestly and respectfully\nurge that present committee be cor\ntinued so that it may contribute its\nexperience to the solution of vexing\nproblems already upon us and may\nat the same time reassure Negrc\ncitizens that the government has\nnot abandoned them and that tht\ndemocracy- their soldiers fought foi\nis at work on the home front.\nUse The Omaha Guide\nAs A\nMo Mum of Advertising\nLABOR DAY MESSAGE\nBy Philip Murray, President CIO\ni On Labor Day, 1945, labor shares\nthe pride of all Americans in the mag\nnificent record of ou rarmed forces, as\nsignalized by the complete defeat of\nthe Japanese and the Nazis. Labor\nhas contributed mightily to these suc\ncesses.\nIn the sphere of international rela\ntions, labor has also done its part for\nthe continuing unity of the United\nNations. The San Francisco Charter\nhas laid a firm foundation for world\norganization against fascism, aggres\nsion and future war, while the World\nConference of Trade Unions has made\nsplendid progress in uniting the work\ning people of all countries for these\nand other common purposes.\nBut on the domestic scene, unfor\ntunately, American labor finds fewer\ngrounds for satisfaction.\nIn its unparallele! war achieve\nments. America has shown a capacity\nfor organization and production that\nshould assure the full employment of\nour people after the war in creating\nunparalleled prosperity for all. But,\nwith reconversion already under way,\nthere are many tragic signs that selfish\nprivilege and governmental inertia are\nobstructing the fulfillment of this\npromise.\nThe mass purchasing power of\nAmerican working people must ob\nbiously be one of the main pillars of\nour postwar prosperity. Yet today this\npurchasing power is being cruelly\nslashed by layoffs, loss of overtime,\ndowngrading and generally reduced\ntake-home pay, while the infamous\nincubus of the Little Steel formula\nsmothers collective bargaining and\nholds wage rates far below sky-high\nliving costs.\nCongress meanwhile has been eager\nand quick to provide profit guarantees\nand other protections for business in\nreconversion, but has not lifted a\nfinger to aid the worst victims of re\nconversion, the laid-off war workers.\nThere is also a lamentable lack of\nnational planning for full employment,\nand a tendency to lift production and\nprice controls in such a way as to re\nstore the \u201cnormalcy\u201d of unlimited\ngrabbing for the few and depression\nand unemployment for the many.\nOn this Labor Day, the CIO calls\nupon our political and industrial lead\ners to join with labor and the whole\nAmerican people in reversing these\ndisastrous trends before it is too late.\nWe urge the immediate revision of\nour national wage policy to permit\nsubstantial wage adjustments, and to\neliminate substandard wages below\n65c an hour.\nM e urge Congress, immediately it\nreconvenes, to adopt President Tru\nman s emergency proposals for $25 a\nweek for 26 weeks for unemployed\nwar workers, as embodied in the Kil\ngore-Forand bill.\ne urge the speedy adoption of the\nguaranteed annual wage in collective\nbargaining agreements throughout in\ndustry.\nSo the American people may have\nfreedom from want and fear, we urge\nexpansion of our social securit; sys\ntem, as proposed in the Murray-Wag\nner-Dingell bill. And to end un\nAmerican discriminations, we call for\na permanent Fair Employment Prac\ntice Commission.\nWe also urge an immediate start on\nover-all planning for full production\nand jobs for all, for which a first step\nis passage of the Murray-Patman Full\nEmployment bill.\nAt the same time, we warn against\nthe national division threatened by\nplans for anti-union drives and by\nsuch anti-labor measures as the Ball\nBurton-Hatch bill, and call instead\nfor national unity and cooperation in\npromoting national prosperity.\nIn the difficult davs ahead, Ameri\nI\ncan labor must above all build its\nunion strength and increase its politi\ncal activity, so that it may make its\nfull contribution to complete victory\nover all anti-democratic forces and tq\na free and prosperous postwar Amer\nica.\nFor the achievement of these goals,\nthe CIO offers its closest cooperation\nto all other Americans who love their\ncountry and seek its welfare.\nNEW YORK\u2014A preliminary check\non the employment situation one\nweek after V-J Day reveals a spotty\npicture, but with thousands of col\nored workers out of jobs, according\nto the NAACP.\nThe NAACP West Coast office in\nSan Francisco reported that the\ngreatest number of Negroes had\nbeen laid off in the Richmond yards\nof the Kaiser Company and that\nfew of these discharged from ship\nconstruction were being reeniploy\ned on ship repair because the A. F.\n1*. unions on ship repair jobs claim\nthe Negroes lack the required\nskills.\nFrom Philadelphia comes a report\nthat two- well known firms, Bayuk\nCigar Company (Phillies) and Sears\nRoebuck have requested \u201cwhite\nonly\u201d employees of the United Stat\nes Employment Service. Bayuk\nasked for 1^00 women and Sears\nRoebuck for 250. but all white. Al\nso from Philadelphia comes the re\nport that many firms are request\ning through the Veterans Adminis\ntration \u201cwhite only\u201d or \u201cwhite Gen\neile only.\nIn Houston, Texas, the picture is\nnot so dark. Many fiv\u2019v.s ive not\ndischarged any workers and some\nhave transferred workers, white\nand Negro, to other plants on peace\ntime production. However. one\nfirm which had 1 000 Negroes now\nhas less than 200. On the other\nhand, several firms in Houston have\nannounced they will employ more\nNegroes.\nChicago reported no trends dis\ncernible in first week after V-J\nDay but that Negroes were being\nlaid off according to seniority, but\nnot on a discriminatory basis.\nPortland, Oregon, reports that\n10,000 employees have left the Kai\nser shipyards, some of their own\nvolition, but that many others\ncould have been absorbed in other\nyards which are still working.\nIn Kansas City, Missouri, cancel\nlation of war contracts with North\nAmerican Aviation and Pratt-Whit\nney has thrown approximately 7,\n200 Negroes out of work.\nCleveland, Ohio, reports that at\nthe end of the first week after V-J\nDay about 7.000 Negroes were but\nof job* and that of this number ap\nproximately 4 000 will not be reem\nployed.\nDismissals in Detroit were report\ned occurring \u201cdaily\u201d with plants\nstaggering the lay offs in order not\nto add to the confusion. Persons\napplying for unemployment insur\nance have lined up for as far as\nseven blocks. The picture on the\nNegro worker was not too clear\none week after V-J Day.\nDue to the fact that about 1400\nUPWA-CIO workers of the Morrell\npacking plant at Ottumwa, Iowa have\nbeen locked out by the company,\nwhich has refused to do collective\nbargaining with the union, Omaha\nPacking House Workers tonighth\nthroug a joint executive board meet\ning of all UPWA-CIO Omaha, Nebr.\nlocals, representing 19,909 packing\nhouse workers, pledged their support\nto the workers of the Morrell Packing\nCo. and demand that government\nagency settle the dispute or action will\nbe taken. The Morrell Packing Co.\nhas signed a contract with the\nUPWA-CIO and has refused to follow\nsame. Also refused to follow orders of\ngovernment agencies.\nJOINT COUNCIL DINING\nCAR EMPLOYEES\nThe Joint Council Dining Car Em\nployes, Richard W. Smith, Secretary\nTreasurer, and its affiliated Local 351,\nof Chicago, Bert Jones, Pres., W. S.\nSeltzer, Gen. Chr., T. C. Edge, Sec.\nTreas., H. T. Brooks, Ed. Dir. bit\nterly denounced a press release ap\npearing in Chicago papers which\nstated that dining car waiters \u201cswin\ndled GIs\u201d on the railroad.\nAt a hearing for dining car work\ners picked up by FBI agents posing\nas railroad stewards, held in the Old\nPost Office Building at 11:00 a. m.\non August 23, under Judge Edwin N.\nWalker, only one man pleaded guilty.\nThe rest of the group emphatically\ndenied the accusations, and later told\ntheir union representative that the\nsmall portions served were due to the\nsmall amounts of food, especially\nmeat, furnished all diners by the Car\nrier. They said that on many occa\nsions no meat was provided but only\negg dishes were served. Many GIs\nwho were accustomed to eating meat\nj >n the army rebelled at the egg and\nvegetable meals, which, of course,\nwas n j fault of the waiters.\nThe Council, and Local 351, em\nphatically stated that the slur in the\npress aws deliberately calculated to;\ncreate the impression that dining car\nworkers conspired to cheat GIs is\nfalse. One of every nine dining car\nworkers is serving in the armed\nforces; many dining car workers have\nlost their lives in World War II and\nseveral thousands more are still in\nthe armed forces; dining car workers\nhave bought several millions of dol\nlars worth of war bonds; they have\nput on special programs for all sorts\nof home front activities and supported\nthe American Red Cross with blood\ndonations and with dollars and cents;\nthey have worked inhumanly long\nhours, oftimes as many as 290 per\nmonth at a time, in crowded, over\nheated trains\u2014sleeping and living in\nunsanitary, cramped quarters, dead\nheading, etc., to feed GIs to whom\nthey have been real friends and\nbrothers.\nThe Joint Council and Local 351\nhave statements from Howard Gould,\nIndustrial Relations Officer of the\nChicago Urban League, O. O. Shands,\nN.A.A.C.P., Rex Gorleigh of the\nSouth Side Community Art Center,\nand a number of heads of reputable\norganizations who know, from day to\nday contact, that dining car work\ners are honest, reputable and fhi st\nworthy citizens who should not be\nmade victims of such slanderous prop\naganda as reflected in the headline\n\u201cGIs swindled.\u201d\n\nOmaha Children to Enjoy\nMatinee Saturday Given\nby Royal American Show\nOmaha children are going to have\na special party on the Royal Ameri\ncan Shows\u2019 midway Saturday after\nnoon at what officials of the Omaha\nVeterans of Foreign Wars call a \u201cbig\nkiddies nickle fun time camical\nparty.\u201d\nChildren and parents will be ad.\nmitted t othe grounds as guests of\nVeterans and free parking for 10,000\ncars has been made available directly\nacross from the showgrounds.\nFor children of school age all\nshows and virtually all of the thrill\nrides will be priced at five cents,\nVeterans told The Guide. Special\nprices will prevail, also, for everyone\nattending the children\u2019s matinee, it\nwas reported.\nRoyal American Shows has been\nplaying to tremendous crowds nightly\never since it opened a week ago. The\nclosing engagement will be Monday,\nLabor Day.\nFamily matinees are scheduled both\nfor Sunday and Monday afternoon.\nOutstanding among all tent the\nater shows on the midway is Leon\nClaxton s famous Cuban Rum Boo\ngie,\u201d featuring a delightful troupe of\nsingers and dancers from Havana,\nCuba, who are on their first tour in\nthe United States.\nJOBS FOR THE ASKIN\nYou Travel Too!\nIf you want a good job and also\nlike to travel here\u2019s an opportunity.\nElsewhere in this edition in an ad\nvertisement signed by Wm. Martin,\nmanager, cookhouse, Royal American\nShows, saying he needs cooks, dish\nwashers, waiters, busmen and other\nhelp to travel with the big show.\nMr. Martin told The Guide the\nshow travels southward through Kan\nsas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Alabama\nto Florida where it will take part in\nall of the Florida midwinter fairs.\nSo, if you like show business and\nenjoy travel, here\u2019s an opportunity for\na few Omahans.\nAMERICAN COUNCIL\nOF RACE RELATIONS\nThe American Council of Race Re\nlations this week went on record as\nendorsing one hundred per cent the\nWagner-Murray full employment bill.\n*4\nBoystown Band to Play;\nSpeaking, Sports, Fun Slated\non Monday\u2019s Workers\u2019Card\n(BY A. B. OOOIII.KTT)\nAll is set for our big Labor Day\nCelebration. The Committee under\nthe able leadership of Jack Cassidy\nis sparing no pains in attempting\nto make this the greatest celebra\ntion in the history of the CIO and\nOmaha.\nHow about making plans to spend\nLabor Day, Monday. September 3,\nwith your fellow CIO members,\ntheir families and friends.\nThis arrangement is under the\nauspices of the City Industrial Un\nion Council. (This including not\nonly the ten thousand workers in\nthe South Omaha Packing Industry\nTransport Workers' Union, but\nmany other workers in the city\ncome under the banners of the\nCIO.\nWe have come a long ways to\nwards making Omaha a Union\nTown. Come and witness some of\nthe fine progress we are making.\nTHE PUBLIC IS CORDIALLY\nINVITED.\nRemember the place, Beautiful\nRiverview Park at 10th and Deer\nPark Boulevard. Program starts\nat 12:30 pm. addressed by national\nleaders of the CIO, Band music by\nthe famous Boystown band. Flag\nceremony by the Seventh Service\nCommand. U. S. Army and Vets of\nWorld War II. There will be\nsports, fun and entertainment.\nStart now to pack that old picnic\nbasket and come to the greatest\nsocial event of the year. You will\nmeet old friends, you will make\nnew friends and have the time of\nyour life.\nwhich, according to A. A. Liverright,\nexecutive director of the Council, is\n\u201cone of the most important corner\nstones of a sound national program\nfor unity and the elimination of racial\ntensions in America.\u201d\nIn a letter addressed to Senator\nRobert F. Wagner, who, iwth Senator\nJames E. Murray, is sponsoring the\nbill, Liveright declared that, \"al\nthough we do not believe that a plan\nfor full employment will automatically\neradicate racial tensions, we are firm\nMISSIONARY CONVENTION\nCONVENE AT BETHEL A.M.E.\nUnder the leadership of Rev. C. II.\nCopeland, Bethel A.M.E. Church,\n16th and Ave. A, Council Bluffs, will\nbe host to the Northwestern Confer\nence and Missionary Convention, in\ntheir 25tli annual session. This will\nbe the first time in 19 years that the\nConference has et there. More than a\nhundred delegates and visitors repre\nsenting Minnesota, Iowa and South\nDakota will be in session from Sept.\n3rd through the 9th. The popular and\ndynamic Bishop J. A. Gregg assisted\nby Presiding Elders: Revs. W. II.\nOgleton and W. E. Guy and also\nMrs. Goldie Fant, president of the\nConference Branch Missionary So\nciety, will preside. Among the dis\ntinguished guests expected to be,\npresent are: Dr. L. L. Berry, Secre\ntary of Missions, New York; Dean\nLewis of Payne Seminary, Wilber\nforce University; Dr. Charles Wesley,\nPresident of Wilberforce U., Mrs.\nNettie Crews Woods, 4th District\nMissionary leader of Chicago, 111.\nand others. Special programs by the\nMissionary Society on Monday and\nTuesday evenings. Wednesday morn\ning the Annual Sermon and Commun\nion Services, followed by the regular\nbusiness sessions and reports from the\nCharges. Wednesday evening Local\nprogram and reception; Thursday\nevening, Missionary program; Friday\nevening, Education Night; Saturday\nthe Junior MiPssionary, and Lay\nmen\u2019s organization will hold ses\nsions, and Sunday winding up the\nmeeting with the reading of Appoint\nments by the Bishop. Committee\nchairmen are as follows: Kitchen and\nfood service, Mrs. Hazel Means; Din\ning room, Mrs. Marybelle Cruse;\nCourtesy, Mrs. Lillie Mills; Program,\nthe Pastor and Organists; Registra\ntion, Mrs. Jeanne Banks; and Hous\ning, Mrs. Ocie Cooper.\nThe 4th Quarterly Meeting and\nConference will be held at Bethel\nA.M.E. Church Sunday, Sept. 2nd.,\npresided over by Rev. W. H. Ogle\nton, Presiding Elder of the Des\nMoines District. Special Services at 3\np. m. at which time Rev. Grant Page\nof Clarinda will bring the message as\nthe guest speaker. Rev. Ogleton will j\ndeliver the morning and evening ser\nmons. Reports for the year will be\nreviewed.\nly convinced that the problem of\ndealing with intergroup relations will\nbe enormously simplified by the elim\nination of unemployment.\u201d\nThe bill, which President Truman\nhas catalogued as \u201cmust\u201d legislation,\nand which has the backing of Secre\ntary of State Byrnes and most labor\ngroups, was up for a hearing before\nthe Senate banking and currency com\nmittee throughout the past week. It\nwas during this hearing that Secre-1\ntary of State Byrnes stated that he\nbelieved in the \u201cgeneral principles\u201d\nof the bill and that its enactment\nwould \u201cdemonstrate to the world\nthat this country is determined to\nprevent mass unemployment.\u201d\nPointing out that \u201clack of security\nis one of the major factors in increas\ning racial tensions,\u201d the American\nCouncil\u2019s eexcutive director assured\nSenator Wagner that the organiza\ntion heartily endorses the proposed\nfull employment legislation and is\nalso in favor of other \u201ceffective na\ntional legislation,\u201d including extension\no fthe Social Security Act, adequate\ncoverage under social security, health\ninsurance, and an adequate housing\nprogram. Our organization,\u201d Liver\nigkt informed Senator Wagner, \u201chas,\nfor at least six months, attempted to\nemphasize the basic importance of\nthe Wagner-Murray Full Employment\nBill to a sound solution to race rela\ntions in this country.\u201d\nUrban Lge Sec\u2019y\nI\nUrges Workers\nTo Register!\nIn the first of a series of tours to\nindustrial plants, Mr. Duward R.\nCrooms, Executive Secretary of the\nOmaha Urban League and Mr. Ar\nthur B. McCaw, Assistant, learned\nthat employees layed oft because of\nwar contract cutbacks will be rehired\naccording to seniority regardless of\nrace at the Eaton Metal Products Co.\nThe Gate City Iron Works had not\nbeen forced to lay off any of its per\nsonnel but were in need of more help\nboth laborers and welders. The In\ndependent Metal Products Co. had\nnot been required to lay off any of\nits employees either. However, they\nare not in need of any help nor have\nthey ever employed any Negroes.\nMr. Crooms and Mr. McCaw in\nterviewed Mr. Paul Smith, assistant\nsuperintendent at Eaton Metal Prod\nucts Co., who praised the work of\ntheir Negro employees saying that the\nfirst person to be rehired will be a\nNegro.\nMr. Crooms announced that Urban\nLeague facilities will be available to\nany one looking for work and urged\nthat all persons available for work\ncome to the League office to register.\nHe said Mr. McCaw are going to con\ntact all other industrial plants and\nbusiness houses for the purpose of\nencouraging the use of Negro labor\nand keep an active file on jobs avail\nable.\nThe Omaha Urban League is sup\nported by the Community Chest.\nMEMORY OF ALICE DAVIS\nAt the request of relatives of the\nlate Mrs. Alice Davis, for more than\nforty years a resident of this city, and\nduring all that time a most staunch\nfriend and client of mine, I wish to\ntake this opportunity of expressing\npublicly, my deep appreciation of\nthat friendship, and my knowledge of\nthe beauties of the sturdy Christian\ncharacter of this outstanding woman.\nAlice was one that di dnot need to\nfear the approach of that moment,\nwhen our Heavenly Father called, to\nher to approach the Judgment Seat,\nand she answered that call by saying,\n\u201cHere, dear Lord; not my will, but\nthine be done.\u201d\nHer whole life was marked by that\ncleanness, charity, beauty of Spirit\nthat made the summons to cross that\ninvisible line that separates Time from\nEternity, a joy. In my heart and Soul\nI feel that I can hear the beautiful\nwords of welcome to the Heavenly\nKingdom uttered by Our Father\u2014\n\u201cWell done, thou good and faithful\nservant, enter into the Kingdom of\nHeaven, prepared from the beginning\nfor all those that know, love, and\nserve God.\u201d\nAlice had no idle moment; she\nraised her family and raised them\nwell and at many sacrifices to her.\nShe was easily the outstanding head\nof the Colored Race of this city, and\ndevoted all time that was not taken\nup with the support and care of her\nfamily to aiding the less fortunate\nmembers of her Race. She worked\nmany long years for the upbuilding\nand support of the Bethel A. M. E.\nChurch which to her was a spot very\nnear to Heaven. She loved her work\nin the Church and by reason of the\nbeauty of her character she has\nbrought happiness to many a member\nof her Race who had become careless\nin respect to his or her duty to Al\nmighty God.\nAlice will be sadly missed by her\nhost o ffriends of both races in this\ncity and Southwestern Iowa, but as\nmembers enjoying the happiness of a\nChristian religion we know that this\nseparation is not final; we know' that\nwe will meet again in that Heavenly\nKingdom where separation is un\nknown.\nI feel at this time, that we should\nnot say, \u201cGoodbye,\u201d but rather, \"fare\nwell, dear Mother and Friend, until\nwe meet again.\nJohn P. Tinley.","height":"31628","width":"23984"}}
